$DATUM 5-(4-Pyrrolidin-1-yl-phenyl)-6-oxa-4-aza-spiro[2.4]hept-4-ene-7-carboxylic
acid methyl-(3-trifluoromethyl-phenyl)-amide (71b): General procedure for
animation of aryl bromide in 70 (GP 11) (Buchwald-Hartwig Reaction): To
an oven-dried Schlenk flask purged with nitrogen, was taken Pd2(dba)3
(2.0 mol %) and (+/-)-BINAP (3.0 mol %) in 5 mL of toluene. The mixture
was heated to 80 degC with stirring for 5 min to dissolve the BINAP.
After cooling, the aryl-bromide (70a or 70b), the corresponding amine and
t-BuONa was added and the mixture was heated to 80 degC for 16 hr. the
mixture was cooled to room temperature, diluted with Et2O (25 mL),
filtered, and concentrated in vacuo. The crude product obtained from 70a
(90.6 mg, 0.20 mmol), Pd2(dba)3 (3.65 mg), (+/-)-BINAP (3.74 mg),
pyrrolidine (28 mg, 0.40 mmol) and t-BuONa (28.8 mg, 0.30 mmol) according
to GP 11 was purified by column chromatography (Rf = 0.42, Et2O) to yield
80 mg (90 %) of 71b as white solid, mp = 152-153 degC.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for Willgerodt-Kindler
Reaction: A mixture of arylglyoxal hydrate 1 (1 mmol), amine 2 (2 mmol)
and elemental sulfur (2 mmol) was heated at 80 °C for 0.6-1 h. After
completion of the reaction, monitored by TLC (n-hexane/EtOAc: 7/3), the
unreacted sulfur was removed by adding of 2 mL EtOH, heating and then hot
filtration. By cooling the filtrate, corresponding α-ketothioamides were
crystallized and separated by simple filtration. Further purification for
elemental analysis was carried out by recrystallization in n-hexane or
EtOH. In the case of oily products, column chromatography was used for
purification. All compounds were characterized using FT-IR, 1H NMR and
13C NMR spectra. Compounds 3a-g, 3j-n, 3r and 3t are new and were
characterized also by elemental analysis.
1-Phenyl-2-(pyrrolidin-1-yl)-2-thioxoethanone (3a): Yellow oil. Yield
90%. FT-IR (KBr): 3100, 2971 (C-H), 1665 (C═O), 1620 (C═C), 1501 (C═S),
1449 (CH2 bending), 1260 (C-N), 1172 (C═S) cm-1. 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3):
δ = 8.01 (d, J = 8.8 Hz, 2H, CHAr), 7.63 (t, J = 7.2 Hz, 1H, CHAr), 7.5
(t, J = 7.6 Hz, 2H, CHAr), 3.99-3.96 (m, 2H, CH2-N), 3.58-3.55 (m, 2H,
CH2-N), 2.14-2.04 (m, 4H, CH2). 13C NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 192.8
(C═S), 188.8 (C═O), 134.2, 132.8, 130.1, 128.9, 51.3, 51.1, 26.1, 23.9.
Anal. Calcd for C12H13NOS: C, 65.72; H, 5.97; N, 6.39. Found: C, 65.64;
H, 6.01; N, 6.87.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES
$DATUM green chemistry, Willgerodt-Kindler reaction, no solvent

$DATUM Method B. Compound 2a (1.02 g, 1.31 mmol) was dissolved in 8mL
pyrrolidine, then K2CO3 (0.27 g, 1.96 mmol) was added. The solution was
stirred at room temperature under dry nitrogen for 30 minute. Excess
pyrrolidine was removed on a rotary evaporator and the residue was column
chromatographed on silica with 2.5:1 chloroform/petroleum ether (V:V).
1-(p-Tert-butylphenoxy)-7-(N-Pyrrolidinyl)-N,N'-Dicyclohexyl-3,4:9,10-Perylenebis(dicarboximide)
(3). Yield: (90%), green product. Rf = 0.55. IR (KBr, cm-1): 2927, 2854,
1693, 1655, 1597, 1506, 1453, 1418, 1384, 1329, 1260, 1238, 1174, 1124,
986, 808, 751, 559. 1H-NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3, ppm) δ 9.38 (d, 1H, J = 8.3
Hz), 8.58 (d, 1H, J = 8.1 Hz), 8.52 (s, 1H), 8.38 (d, 1H, J = 8.3 Hz),
8.29 (s, 1H), 7.62 (d, 1H, J = 8.1 Hz), 7.45 (d, 2H, J = 8.7 Hz), 7.11
(d, 2H, J = 8.7 Hz), 5.05 (m, 2H), 3.77(m, 2H), 2.81 (m, 2H), 2.56 (m,
4H), 2.15 (m, 8H), 1.86 (m, 8H), 1.73 (m, 6H) 1.36 (s, 2H), 1.22 (s, 9H).
13C-NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3, ppm): δ 164.5, 164.4, 164.2, 163.8, 154.3, 153.1,
148.1, 147.9, 135.3, 131.9, 129.5, 128.3, 127.4, 127.1, 125.5, 124.3,
124.0, 123.5, 122.5, 121.6, 119.1, 116.7, 115.1, 54.1, 52.8, 52.5, 34.6,
31.6, 30.2, 29.5, 29.3, 26.7, 25.6. MS (MALDI): m/z = 771.7 [M]+. Anal.
Calcd for C50H49N3O5: C, 77.80; H, 6.40; N, 5.44. Found: C, 77.59; H,
6.26; N, 5.42. λmax in different solvents (1.0 × 10-5M): Toluene: 638
(nm), Chloroform: 648 (nm), THF: 635 (nm), Cyclohexane: 617 (nm).

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Preparation of
6-bromo-2-[2-(pyrrolidin-1-yl)ethyl]-3,4-dihydroisoquinolin-1(2H)-one A
stirred solution of
2-(6-bromo-1-oxo-3,4-dihydroisoquinolin-2(1H)-yl)acetaldehyde (2.7 g, 11
mmol) and pyrrolidine (1.24 mL, 16.5 mmol) in methanol (40 mL) was
treated with NaBH3CN (0.95 g, 16.5 mmol) and acetic acid (1.44 mL, 27.5
mmol) at room temperature, stirred overnight, diluted with CH2Cl2 and
washed with saturated NaHCO3. The aqueous layer was extracted with
methylene chloride. The combined organic layers were washed with brine,
dried over Na2SO4 and concentrated in vacuo. The residue was purified by
ISCO CombiFlash® chromatography (silica, 0-10% methanol in methylene with
0.5% ammonium hydroxide). Step 1:
6-Iodo-2-(2-(Pyrrolidin-1-yl)ethyl)-3,4-dihydroisoquinolin-1(2H)-one
Using essentially the same procedure described in step 4 of Example 143
and employing pyrrolidine (1.98 g, 6.3 mmol), the title compound 1.0 g
(90%) was obtained as a white foam. MS (ES) m/z 371.0 [M+H]+.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM 1,3-diphenylpropan-2-one O-perfluorobenzoyl oxime 9 To a stirred solution
of diphenylacetone (1.0 eq.) in dry ethanol was added dropwise pyridine
(2.0 eq.) followed by hydroxylamine hydrochloride (1.5 eq.). The solution
was heated under reflux for 18h until TLC shows the complete
disapparition of the ketone. The reaction mixture was cooled to room
temperature and quenched with water. The aqueous layer was extracted 3
times with EtOAc and the combined organic layers were washed with brine,
dried over sodium sulfate and evaporated under reduced pressure. The
residue was then crystallized from ethanol to afford the corresponding
oxime. Due to its relative instability, the structure of the oxime was
confirmed by 1H NMR and the product directly engaged on the next step. To
an ice-cold solution of the oxime (1.0 eq.) and Et3N (1.5 eq.) in dry
CH2Cl2 was added dropwise pentafluorobenzoyl chloride (1.1 eq.). The
mixture was stirred for 2h at 0°C until TLC shows the complete
disapparition of the oxime. The reaction was quenched with a saturated
aqueous solution of NaHCO3 and the aqueous layer was extracted 3 times
with dichloromethane. The combined organic layers were washed with brine,
dried over magnesium sulfate and evaporated under reduced pressure to
give a light brown oil. This residue was purified by chromatography on
silica gel (heptane: EtOAc 95:5). The desired compound in 97% yield as a
colorless oil. R f =0.34 (9:1 heptane:EtOAc); IR (neat, cm-1) ν 1775,
1651, 1522, 1494, 1323, 1195, 1088, 994, 859, 699; ¹H-NMR (CDCl3, 300
MHz) δ 7.34-7.23 (m, 8H), 7.13 (d, J=7.5 Hz, 2H), 3.77 (s, 2H), 3.66 (s,
2H); ¹³C-NMR (CDCl3, 75.5 MHz) δ 168.8, 156.7, 145.4 (dm, J=257 Hz, 2C),
143.4 (dm, J=257 Hz), 137.7 (dm, J=257 Hz, 2C), 134.8, 134.2, 129.3 (2C),
129.0 (2C), 128.9 (2C), 128.8 (2C), 127.3, 127.2, 107.0 (m), 39.2, 34.6;
HRMS (m/z, ES+) calcd for C22H14NO2F5Na ([M+Na]+) 442.0842, found
442.0841.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

$DATUM 64-17-5
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Preparation of
2-Dialkylamino-3,5,6,8-tetrahydro-4H-thiopyrano[4',3':4,5]thieno[2,3-d]pyrimidin-4-ones
6a-6i To a solution of iminophosphorane 3 (1.01 g, 2 mmol) in anhydrous
CH2Cl2 (10 mL), aromatic isocyanate (2 mmol) was added under nitrogen
atmosphere at room temperature. After the reaction mixture was left
unstirred for 6-12 h at 0-5°C, the iminophosphorane 3 had disappeared
(TLC monitored). The solvent was removed under reduced pressure and
Et2O/petroleum ether (1:2, 20 mL) was added to precipitate
triphenylphosphine oxide. Removal of the solvent gave carbodiimides 4,
which were used directly without further purification. To the solution of
4 in dichloromethane (10 mL) was added dialkylamine (2 mmol). After the
reaction mixture was left unstirred for 4-6 h, the solvent was removed
and anhydrous EtOH (10 mL) with several drops of EtONa in EtOH was added.
The mixture was stirred for 6-12 h at room temperature. The solution was
condensed, and the residue was recrystallized from EtOH to give the
expected cyclic compounds 6a-6i in good yields.
3-(4-Fluorophenyl)-2-(1-pyrrolidinyl)-3,5,6,8-tetrahydro-4H-thiopyrano[4',3':4,5]thieno[2,3-d]pyrimidin-4-ones
(6i) Colorless crystals, yield 90% m.p. 220-222°C, 1H NMR (CDCl3, 600
MHz) δ 1.72-1.78 (m, 4H, CH2CH2), 2.91 (t, 2H, J = 6.0 Hz, CH2), 3.05 (t,
4H, J = 6.0 Hz, 2NCH2), 3.21 (t, 2H, J = 6.0 Hz, CH2), 3.76 (s, 2H, CH2),
7.15-7.30 (m, 4H, Ar-H); IR (cm-1), 1685, 1529, 1344, 1217; MS m/z (%),
387 (100, M+), 354 (39), 149 (24), 95 (24). Elemental Anal. Calcd. for
C19H18FN3OS2: C, 58.89; H, 4.68; N, 10.84. Found: C, 58.72; H, 4.41; N,
10.91.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):NOTES

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 3) Preparation of
3-(1-chloro-3,4-dihydronapth-2-yl)-acrylic acid piperidide. To the
compound 3-(1-chloro-3,4-dihydronaphth-2-yl) acrylic acid (500mg,
2.31mmol) in dry benzene (50 ml) added freshly distilled thionyl chloride
(1.0 ml) and refluxed for 1hr, excess of thionyl chloride removed in
vacuo and thereafter condensed with dry benzene solution of piperidine
(1.0 ml) and stirred for 30 min. The organic layer washed with water
(2×25 ml), dried over anhydrous sodium sulfate and evaporated on rotary
evaporator to give crude product, which was purified on silica gel column
using pet. ether 60-80 °C: ethyl acetate (90:10) as an eluent to gave the
title compound. Synthesis of 3-(1-chloro-3,4-dihydronapth-2-yl)-acrylic
acid pyrrolidide of formula 1 where R1=R2=R3=R4=H, R=Cl and R5+R6
=pyrrolidine. This was similarly prepared, as described in example 1,
except the starting materials were
3-(1-chloro-3,4-dihydronapth-2-yl)-acrylic acid and pyrrolidide. Yield
(90%). Analysed for C18H20ClNO; calcd C 71.63 H 6.68 Cl 11:75 N 4.64%,
found C71.99 H 6.82 Cl 12.11 N 4.66%. 1H NMR (CDCl3): δ 1.96 (4H, m),
2.66 (2H, t, J=5.0 Hz), 2.89 (2H, t, J=5.0 Hz), 3.51 (2H, t, J=6.5 Hz),
3.65 (2H, t, J=6.5 Hz), 6.57 (1H, d, J=15.36 Hz), 7.25 (3H, m), 7.70 (1H,
d, J=2.76 Hz), 8.06 (1H, d, J=15.3 Hz).

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: 3) Preparation of
3-(1-bromo-3,4-dihydronapth-2-yl)-acrylic acid piperidide. To the
compound 3-(1-bromo-3,4-dihydro-napth-2-yl)-acrylic acid (500mg,
2.31mmol) in dry benzene (15 ml) added freshly distilled thionyl chloride
(0.53 ml) and refluxed for 1hr, excess of thionyl chloride removed in
vacuo and thereafter condensed with dry benzene solution of piperidine
(1.0 ml) and stirred for 30 min. The organic layer was washed with water
(2×25 ml), dried over anhydrous sodium sulfate, concentrated to give
crude product, which was purified on silica gel column using pet. ether:
ethyl acetate (92:8) as an eluent to gave the title compound. Synthesis
of 3-(1-bromo-3,4-dihydronapth-2-yl)-acrylic acid pyrrolidide of formula
1 where R1=R2=R3=R4=H, R=Br and R5+R6=pyrrolidine. This was similarly
prepared, as described in example 24, except the starting materials were
3-(1-bromo-3,4-dihydronapth-2-yl)-acrylic acid and pyrrolidine. Yield
(90%). Analysed for C17H18BrNO; calcd C 61.46 H 5.46 Br 24.05 N 4.22%,
found C 62.41 H 5.49 Br 24.08 N 4.36%.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure:
(+)-(6-(Azidomethyl)-5-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-7-methylimidazo-[1,2-a]pyrimidin-2-yl)(morpholino)methanone.
To a stirred solution of 23 (150 mg, 0.400 mmol) in THF (10 mL) was added
morpholine (52.2 μL, 0.597 mmol), HOAt (81.3 mg, 0.597 mmol), EDAC (114
mg, 0.597 mmol), and iPr2NEt (138 μL, 0.795 mmol). The reaction was kept
at RT for 2 h and was concentrated under reduced pressure. The residue
was diluted with EtOAc, and the organic layer was washed with 1N HCl, 1N
NaOH, and brine prior to drying over anhydrous MgSO4. Filtration and
concentration under reduced pressure afforded the amide (177 mg, 99%
crude yield) as a clear glass. A small amount was purified by silica gel
chromatography (100% EtOAc) to afford the product (99%purity, >99% ee).
(+)-(6-(Aminomethyl)-5-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-7-methylimidazo-[1,2-a]pyrimidin-2-yl)(morpholino)methanone
(24c). To a stirred solution of the above amide (177 mg, 0.397 mmol) in
THF (8 mL) and H2O (0.8 mL) was added PPh3 polymer bound (3 mmol/g, 199
mg, 0.600 mmol) and heated to 50°C for 24 h. The reaction was filtered,
concentrated under reduced pressure, and purified by reverse phase HPLC
to give 24c, TFA salt (121 mg, 56% yield, >99% ee) as a white solid. 24b
1H NMR (400 MHz, CD3OD) δ 7.90 (d, J = 1.8 Hz, 1H), 7.72 (dd, J = 1.8,
8.4 Hz, 1H), 7.68 (d, J = 8.4 Hz, 1H), 7.65 (s, 1H), 4.25 (d, J = 14.9
Hz, 1H), 4.04 (d, J = 14.9 Hz, 1H), 3.87 (t, J = 6.6 Hz, 2H), 3.60 (t, J
= 6.6 Hz, 2H), 2.88 (s, 3H), 1.97 (m, 4H). 13C NMR (100 MHz, CD3OD) δ
165.7, 163.2, 162 (TFA), 148.0, 145.8, 141.1, 140.7, 136.0, 134.2, 132.7,
131.0, 128.0, 120 (TFA), 118.0, 114.9, 37.9, 28.0, 25.4, 24.6. Anal.
Calcd for C19H19Cl2N5O2·2TFA: C, 43.69; H, 3.35; N, 11.08. Found: C,
43.70; H, 3.47; N, 11.17.

PPh3 used in stage 2

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: General Procedure for the Preparation of the
S3, S6a-c, S10a-c, S13a-c and S15a-c. To a stirred suspension of
dimethylamine hydrochloride (16.61 mmol), pyrrolidine (16.61 mmol) or
morpholine (16.61 mmol) in CH2Cl2(30 mL) (for S6c, toluene was used as
solvent) at 0°C was added TEA (41.54 mmol) (for S6c, no TEA was added)
and stirred for 10 min under nitrogen atmosphere. To it, a bromo compound
S2 (13.85 mmol), S5 (13.85 mmol), S9 (13.85 mmol), S12 (13.85 mmol) or
S14 (13.85 mmol) in CH2Cl2 (20 mL) was added and stirred for 30 min. The
mixture was allowed to warm to room temperature and stirred for an
additional 1.5-2 h (for S6c, refluxed for 2 h). The reaction mixture was
washed with saturated NaHCO3 solution (20 mL), dried over anhydrous
Na2SO4, and then evaporated to dryness under reduce pressure. The residue
was purified by MPLC on silica gel. The titled compounds.
1-(4-Fluoro-3-nitrophenyl)-N,N-dimethylmethanamine (S3). The residue was
purified by MPLC on silica gel using CH2Cl2/MeOH (20:1) as eluent.
3-Nitro-5-(pyrrolidin-1-ylmethyl)benzonitrile (S15b). The residue was
purified by MPLC on silica gel using hexane/EtOAc (1:1) as eluent. The
titled compound as a yellow solid. Yield 90%. 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3) δ
8.45 (br s, 1H), 8.39 (br t, 1 H, J = 1.6 Hz), 8.02 (br s, 1 H), 3.78 (s,
2 H), 2.56 (br s, 4 H), 1.84 (br s, 4 H); IR (KBr) 2239, 1540, 1353 cm-1;
HRMS-ESI m/z [M+H]+ calcd. for C12H14N3O2: 232.1081, found 232.1077.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE

(EW-7197): A Highly Potent, Selective, and Orally Bioavailable Inhibitor
of TGF-β Type I Receptor Kinase as Cancer Immunotherapeutic/Antifibrotic
Agent

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM To a stirred solution of 3-(bromomethyl)-5-nitrobenzonitrile (1.50 g,
6.22 mmol) and pyrrolidine (0.53 g, 7.46 mmol) in CH2Cl2 (15 mL) was
added triethylamine (1.88 g, 18.68 mmol) dropwise at 0°C, and the mixture
was stirred at room temperature overnight. The reaction mixture was
evaporated to dryness under reduced pressure, and the residue was diluted
with water (15 mL) and extracted with EtOAc (3 x 50 mL). The EtOAc
solution was dried over anhydrous Na2SO4, filtered, and evaporated to
dryness under reduced pressure. The residue was purified by MPLC on
silica gel using a mixture of EtOAc and hexane as eluent to give
3-nitro-5-(pyrrolidin-1-ylmethyl)benzonitrile. Yellow solid, yield 1.30
g, 90% 1H NMR (400 MHz, CDCl3): δ 8.45 (br s, 1 H), 8.39 (br t, 1 H, J=
1.6 Hz), 8.02 (br s, 1 H), 3.78 (s, 2 H), 2.56 (br s, 4 H), 1.84 (br s, 4
H).

and/or ALK4 inhibitors

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Reaction of N-Aryl-2-nitrosoanilines 1 with
Amines; General Procedure. A N-aryl-2-nitrosoaniline 1 (0.5 mmol) was
dissolved in MeCN (10 mL) and the appropriate amine (2.5 mmol) was added,
except for benzylamine (64 mg, 0.6 mmol) added along with Et3N (121 mg,
1.2 mmol). The mixture was stirred at r.t. for the time specified in
Table 1. After the reaction was complete, the mixture was poured into H2O
(50 mL) and extracted with EtOAc (3 × 50 mL). The combined extracts were
washed with H2O (100 mL) and brine (50 mL), then dried with Na2SO4, and
the solvent was evaporated. The crude product was purified by silica gel
column chromatography (hexane-EtOAc, 4:1 → 1:1, unless otherwise
specified).
N-(4-Ethoxyphenyl)-3-methoxy-2-nitroso-5-(pyrrolidin-1-yl)aniline (2q).
Chromatography eluent: acetone. Dark red solid; yield: 153 mg (90%);
Reactant: 1j, Conditions: MeOH, r.t. Time: 3h. mp 168-169 °C. 1H NMR (500
MHz, CDCl3): δ = 1.43 (t, J = 7.0 Hz, 3 H), 1.90-2.04 (m, 4 H), 3.2-3.7
(m, 4 H), 4.01 (s, 3 H), 4.03 (q, J = 7.0 Hz, 2 H), 5.42 (d, J = 2.1 Hz,
1 H), 5.56 (d, J = 2.1 Hz, 1 H), 6.86-6.90 (m, 2 H), 7.15-7.18 (m, 2 H),
13.84 (br s, 1 H). 13C NMR (125 MHz, CDCl3): δ = 14.8, 25.1, 48.2, 56.0,
63.6, 83.0, 86.7, 115.1, 126.4, 130.7, 141.8, 145.2, 155.5, 156.7, 163.6.
MS (EI, 70 eV): m/z (%) = 341 (20), 327 (100), 323 (14). HRMS (EI): m/z
calcd for C19H23N3O3: 341.1739; found: 341.1735.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Pt-Catalyzed Substitution of Allyl Fluoride
11. Dimethyl[2-(4-tert-Butylphenyl)prop-2-en-1-yl]malonate (12a). A
solution of sodium dimethyl malonate (0.34 mmol) in THF (1 mL), prepared
from dimethyl malonate (39 μL, 0.34 mmol) and NaH (60% in mineral oil,
13.6 mg, 0.34 mmol), was added to a stirred solution of Pt(PPh6)4 (0.01
mmol, 5 mol %) in THF (1 mL), followed by the addition of 11 (38 mg, 0.2
mmol). The reaction mixture was stirred atroom temperature for 1 h. The
reaction was quenched by addition of distilled water and the aqueous
layer extracted two times with Et2O. The combined organic layers were
dried over MgSO4 and solvent removed in vacuo. Silica gel column
chromatography (hexane-diethyl ether, 7:3).
1-(2-(4-tert-Butylphenyl)allyl)pyrrolidine (12c). Following the procedure
of platinum-catalyzed aminotion of 11, the reaction was carried out with
28 μL of pyrrolidine. Silica gel column chromatography (hexane-diethyl
ether, 1:1) yielded 12c (44 mg, 90%) as a colorless oil. 1H NMR (400 MHz,
CDCl3): δ 7.50 (2H, d, J= 8.5 Hz), 7.32 (2H, d, J= 8.5 Hz), 5.42 (1H, s),
5.26 (1H, s), 3.48 (2H, s), 2.56 (4H, m), 1.78 (4H, m), 1.33 (9H, s). 13C
NMR (100 MHz, CDCl3): δ 150.3, 145.2, 137.6, 125.8, 125.1, 113.7, 60.7,
54.2, 34.5, 31.3, 23.6. IR (CH2Cl2): ν 1265. HRMS: m/z calcd for [M+H]+
244.2060, found 244.2062.
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):TITLE
$DATUM Platinum-Catalyzed Substitution of Allylic Fluorides
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):AUTHOR
$DATUM Benedetto, Elena; Keita, Massaba; Tredwell, Matthew; Hollingworth,
Charlotte; Brown, John M.; Gouverneur, Veronique
$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):REFERENCE(1):CITATION
$DATUM Organometallics (2012), 31(4), 1408-1416

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure: Reaction of vinylogous substitution in
chlorovinyldiketones (IVa-IVc) with amines. To the solution of 1 mmol of
chlorovinyldiketone IIIa-IIIc in 15 ml of chloroform 2 mmol of amine was
added. The reaction mixture was stirred for 2-3 h (TLC control) at room
temperature, washed with water (2×5 ml), dried over magnesium sulfate,
solvent removed under reduced pressure, the residue was crystallized from
the mixture ether-hexane. Endocyclic enaminodiketones Va-Vr were obtained
as colorless crystals in 78-90% yield. IR, 1H, 13C, 19F NMR spectra of
compounds Va-Vr are given in the table.
5,5-Dimethyl-3-(pyrrolidin-1-yl)-2-(3-fluorobenzoyl)-2-cyclohexen-1-one
(Vi). Yield 90%. Mp 184-187°C. Found, %: C 72.29; H 7.00; N 4.41.
C19H22NO2F. Calculated, %: C 72.36; H 7.03; N 4.44. IR spectrum, ν, cm-1:
1650, 1615, 1530. 1H NMR spectrum, δ, ppm: 1.14 s (6H, 2CH3), 1.88 m (4H,
2CH2), 2.26 s (2H, CH2), 2.55 s (2H, CH2), 3.21 m (4H, 2CH2), 7.14 m (1H,
Harom), 7.35 m (1H, Harom), 7.52 m (1H, Harom), 7.62 m (1H, Harom). 13C
NMR spectrum, δ, ppm: 25.3, 28.6, 31.5, 44.1, 50.7, 60.7, 110.6, 115.6 d
(J 22), 118.5 d (J 22), 125.0, 129.6 d (J 8), 142.5 d (J 6), 162.7 d (J
246), 163.2, 194.7, 196.5 19F NMR, δ, ppm: -108.20 m.

$DATUM General/Typical Procedure:
(S)-1-Dimethylamino-3-{2-[2-(5-methyl-[1,2,4]triazolo[1,5-a]pyridin-2-yl)-ethyl]-4-thiophen-2-yl-imidazol-1-yl}-propan-2-ol
To a solution of
(R)-1-Chloro-3-{2-[2-(5-methyl-[1,2,4]triazolo[1,5-a]pyridin-2-yl)-ethyl]-4-thiophen-2-yl-imidazol-1-yl}-propan-2-ol
(2 mg, 0.005 mmol) in DMSO (0.5 mL) was added a 2M solution of
dimethylamine in methanol (100 μL, 0.2 mmol), the reaction vessel was
capped and stirred at 100°C for 30 minutes. The volatiles were removed in
vacuo and the residue purified by preparative LC-MS to yield the title
compound.

$DTYPE RXN:VAR(1):EXP_PROC
$DATUM General procedure for the ring opening of methyl
1-nitro-2-arylcyclopropane carboxylates with amines under Lewis acid
catalysis. In a 2-mL microwave vial containing a magnetic stirbar,
cyclopropane 1 (0.23 mmol, 1 equiv) was mixed with the appropriate amine
(0.34 mmol, 1.5 equiv), and dichloromethane (100 μL) was added, followed
by Ni(ClO4)2·6H2O (8.3 mg, 0.023 mmol, 0.1 equiv). The vial was sealed
with a Teflon-lined cap to prevent solvent evaporation (a regular septum
is sufficient on a larger scale), and the reaction mixture was stirred at
room temperature for 17 h. The crude reaction mixture was evaporated
under reduced pressure and purified by flash chromatography. In cases
where the remaining excess of the aniline derivative was difficult to
separate by flash chromatography, it was removed by the following aqueous
workup prior to chromatographic purification: the organic layer was
washed twice with 3 M HCl and the combined acidified aqueous layers were
washed with diethyl ether twice. Combined organic layers were then
neutralized with sat. aq. NaHCO3, washed with sat. aq. NaCl and dried
over Na2SO4. Methyl 2-nitro-4-phenyl-4-pyrrolidin-1-ylbutanoate (3m). The
title compound was prepared by the Lewis acid-catalyzed procedure
described above using cyclopropane (±)-1a (50.0 mg, 0.23 mmol, 1 equiv)
and pyrrolidine (39.5 μL, 0.48 mmol, 2.1 equiv), stirring the reaction
mixture for 48 hours. It was purified by flash chromatography, eluting
with 5% MeOH in dichloromethane, to afford spectroscopically pure 3m as a
yellow oil (60.5 mg, 0.21 mmol, 90%, 60:40 dr). Rf = 0.30 (5% MeOH in
dichloromethane); 1H NMR (300 MHz, CDCl3, mixture of 2 diastereomers) δ
7.40- 7.22 (m, 5H), 5.22 (mc, 1Hd1), 4.83 (dd, 3 J = 3.4 Hz, 3 J = 11.0
Hz, 1Hd2), 3.82 (s, 3Hd1), 3.76 (s, 3Hd2), 3.50 (mc, 1Hd1), 3.19 (dd, 3 J
= 4.6 Hz, 3 J = 10.0 Hz, 1Hd2), 3.06 (mc, 1Hd1), 2.92 (mc, 1Hd2),
2.68-2.35 (m, 5H), 1.79-1.66 (m, 4H); 13C NMR (75 MHz, CDCl3, mixture of
2 diastereomers) δ 165.2, 165.1, 139.7, 138.0, 128.7, 128.4, 128.3,
128.1, 127.9, 85.9, 85.6, 66.0, 63.9, 53.5, 53.4, 52.1, 50.2, 36.0, 35.0,
23.2, 23.0; FTIR (neat) 2959, 2795, 1754, 1561, 1454, 1436, 1262, 1210,
1135, 884, 704 cm-1; HRMS Calcd for C15H21N2O4 (M+H)+: 293.1496. Found
293.1498.
